<section class="section section-tight">
  <div class="container two-col-grid">
    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">What separates a great resume writer from a generic one</h2>
      <p>Most resume writing services follow a template. They replace passive language with action verbs, add numbers where they can find them, and reformat the document to look cleaner. This is not what makes a resume competitive for $100K–$350K roles.</p>
      <p>What makes a resume competitive is strategic repositioning — ensuring that every line of the document positions you as the right candidate for the specific roles you are targeting. This requires understanding how hiring managers and recruiters actually evaluate resumes at each level, not how resume writers think they do.</p>
      <p>Steve Ngoumnai, founder of Askia, spent over a decade on the hiring side — building teams, reviewing thousands of resumes, and making offers at every level from IC through executive. That is the perspective that informs every resume Askia writes.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">Who needs a professional resume writer</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>Professionals targeting a promotion or level-up — the resume needs to communicate the next level, not just the current one</li>
        <li>Career changers who need to reframe experience across function or industry</li>
        <li>Mid-to-senior professionals applying consistently without getting responses</li>
        <li>Executives and Directors targeting $150K–$350K who need organizational-scale impact language</li>
        <li>Tech professionals (engineers, PMs, data, DevOps) whose resumes read like job descriptions instead of achievement records</li>
        <li>Anyone who has been in the same role for 3+ years and needs to reactivate their profile for the market</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-tight">
  <div class="container two-col-grid">
    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">Resume writing service vs. resume writer vs. resume review</h2>
      <p><strong>Resume review:</strong> A diagnostic. We assess what is not working and why, and provide specific prioritized feedback.</p>
      <p><strong>Professional resume writer:</strong> Done-with-you. We rebuild the content together through a structured coaching process — not handed off to a writer who never speaks to you.</p>
      <p><strong>Resume writing service:</strong> The full deliverable — a rewritten, positioned, ATS-optimized resume ready to deploy into your job search.</p>
      <p>At Askia, resume writing is always done with the client, not for them. The result is a resume that you understand, can speak to in interviews, and can iterate on as the search evolves.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">What the best resume writing services get wrong</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong>Writer-to-client handoff model</strong> — A writer who does not know your industry or your hiring market produces generic output</li>
        <li><strong>Template-first approach</strong> — Beautiful formatting that fails ATS parsing or obscures the content that actually matters</li>
        <li><strong>No interview coaching</strong> — A resume that gets you to an interview is useless if you cannot perform in the interview</li>
        <li><strong>No positioning strategy</strong> — Most services rewrite the resume without answering "what role are you actually trying to land, and are you positioned to get it?"</li>
        <li><strong>No market knowledge</strong> — Resume writers without hiring-side experience cannot know what a hiring manager at your target level actually looks for</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

